                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d160">
                <head>160. Memorandum of a Telephone Conversation Between the Secretary of State and
                    the Director of the Bureau of the Budget (<persName corresp="#p_BDE1"
                        >Bell</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d160fn1">Source:
                        Department of State, <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> Files: Lot
                        72 D 192, Telephone Calls. Transcribed by Phyllis D. Bernau of the Office of
                        the Secretary.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1961-10-12T14:57:00-04:00"
                                >October 12, 1961, 2:57 p.m.</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Sec said Viet-Nam can be critical and we would like to throw in resources
                    rather than people if we can. Can we in the Depts involved if the Pres directs
                    it be done put the costs on it on a chit and go to Congress in early January for
                    the necessary special action? B said no problem at all with respect to Defense.
                    They have special authority for military aid. <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                        >CIA</gloss> no problem. Contingency fund exists for State and economic aid
                    so that should mean this is all right. If the Sec wants a more precise answer B
                    should put Hansen<note n="2" xml:id="d160fn2">Assistant Director of the Bureau
                        of the Budget, Kenneth R. Hansen.</note> in touch with whoever is working on
                    it and it should be worked out before they go too far down the road.</p>
            </div>
